<body>

<header>
    <h1>Conti 10 Bridge Group</h1>
    <p>Profit Sharing Explained – Simple, Fair & Transparent</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

    <div class="card">
        <h2>Purpose of This Page</h2>
        <p>
            This page explains how <strong>Conti 10 Bridge Group</strong> shares profits from its business activities.
            The goal is to make everything clear, fair, and easy for every member to understand.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h2>When Profits Are Shared</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Profits are shared <strong>once per year</strong>.</li>
            <li>Sharing happens only <strong>after saving money for the group</strong>.</li>
            <li>No profits are shared without approval by members.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h2>Group Capital (Savings First)</h2>
        <p>
            Before any member receives profit, the group must save part of it.
        </p>
        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Minimum 30%</strong> of total profit is kept as <strong>group capital</strong>.
        </div>
        <p>This money is used for:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Business expansion</li>
            <li>Emergencies</li>
            <li>New projects</li>
            <li>Buying group assets</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> Group capital is not shared among members.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h2>How Remaining Profits Are Shared</h2>
        <p>
            The remaining profit is shared based on effort and commitment, not equally.
        </p>
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Category</th>
                <th>Percentage</th>
                <th>What It Means</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Contribution</td>
                <td>60%</td>
                <td>How well a member contributes money and resources</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Attendance</td>
                <td>20%</td>
                <td>How regularly a member attends meetings</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Participation</td>
                <td>20%</td>
                <td>How active a member is in group activities</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h2>Example Scenario</h2>
        <p><strong>Total yearly profit:</strong> KES 100,000</p>
        <ul>
            <li>30% saved as group capital → <strong>KES 30,000</strong></li>
            <li>Profit to be shared → <strong>KES 70,000</strong></li>
        </ul>
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Category</th>
                <th>Amount (KES)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Contribution (60%)</td>
                <td>42,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Attendance (20%)</td>
                <td>14,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Participation (20%)</td>
                <td>14,000</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h2>Member Scenarios</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Active member:</strong> Gets a higher share.</li>
            <li><strong>Money-only member:</strong> Gets less profit.</li>
            <li><strong>Attendance-only member:</strong> Gets a small share.</li>
            <li><strong>Dormant member:</strong> Gets very little or no profit.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h2>Final Approval</h2>
        <p>
            Profit sharing must be discussed openly and approved at the
            <strong>Annual General Meeting (AGM)</strong>.
        </p>
        <div class="highlight">
            No leader or individual is allowed to distribute profits alone.
        </div>
    </div>

</div>

